<h2>Frequently Asked Questions — LG Washer dE Error</h2>

<h3>What does the dE code mean on my LG washer?</h3>
<p>dE means the washer can't confirm the door is locked, so it won't start the cycle. It's a door or lock fault — frequently just something caught in the seal, sometimes a failed latch — not a problem with washing or draining. You may also see it as dE1 or dE2 on some models.</p>

<h3>Can I fix an LG washer dE error myself?</h3>
<p>Often, yes. Open the door, check the rubber seal and latch for any laundry pinched in the way, wipe the latch area clean, and push the door firmly shut until it clicks. Power-cycle the washer; if it locks and dE clears, you're done.</p>

<h3>How much does it cost to fix an LG washer dE error?</h3>
<p>If it's something caught in the door or a misalignment, it's a quick service call with the $65 diagnostic waived when we do a repair. If the door lock assembly has failed, replacement runs $250–320 installed. We confirm on-site before any work. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Why does my LG washer say dE even when the door looks shut?</h3>
<p>The latch can look closed while the lock switch inside isn't actually engaging — a worn latch, a sagging door, or a small obstruction keeps the switch from confirming. The control only starts when that switch closes, so a door that "looks" shut still throws dE. We test the switch directly to confirm.</p>

<h3>Can I still use my LG washer with a dE error?</h3>
<p>No — it won't run a cycle at all until it confirms the door is locked, so there's no working around it. Check for anything caught in the seal first; if dE stays, the lock assembly needs replacing before the washer will start.</p>

